docs.text: an attempt at florida film noir , palmetto fails at the most fundamental levels .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it's slow moving , uninvolving , and plain just uninteresting .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: harry barber ( woody harrelson ) is an ex-newspaper man , just out of jail after being framed for a crime .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: his luck hasn't been the best , but things are looking up when a mysterious woman , rhea malroux ( elisabeth shue ) , approaches him with a proposition .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: she wants harry to help her and her stepdaughter , odette ( chloe sevigny ) , pull off a fake kidnapping scheme to get $500 , 000 out of her stingy , but rich , husband felix ( rolf hoppe ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: at first , all harry is expected to do is provide a threatening voice on the phone , and to collect the money ( of which he gets to keep 10% ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: but , as the deed is carried out , things are not what they seem , and harry gets caught in the ensuing storm .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: palmetto pulls out all the stops to achieve a film noir film , but the effect never quite comes together .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it's got the sultry florida heat , seductive women , and even curvier plot twists , but the whole thing smells of paint-by-numbers .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: sure , the right ingredients are there , but the end result is much too artificial .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: a lot of the problems lie with the script , which , though providing some genuine surprises , is packed full of leaden dialogue and bland situations .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: even the plot twists don't seem to flow well with the rest of the story .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: some of them , for example , come from so far afield that they seemingly only make sense because the writer needed a twist ( for example : harry's spontaneous job offer , or the whole typewriter situation ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the characters are mostly lifeless , played to type , but not much more .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: woody harrelson plays harry with such imbecilic thick-headedness that it's hard to even picture him as an ex-journalist .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: elisabeth shue vamps it up , but doesn't add anything special to the role .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: chloe sevigny gives a terrible performance , trying to be a sexy 17-year old , but she just leaves a bad taste in your mouth .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: some of the supporting cast ( notably gina gershon and michael rapaport ) give stronger , but , in the end , meaningless performances .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: and to top it off , the pacing of the film is much too slow .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: as the movie grinds to a halt , you're given too much time to wonder why you're wasting it watching palmetto .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: if you're in the mood for this type of movie , you'd be much better off going out and renting some classic film noir .
docs.label: negative
